  "text": "On modern manycore systems with a large number of slower cores, MS-BFS-Graft algorithm scales even better than other maximum matching algorithms. Fig 9 shows the strong scaling of three matching algorithms on the KNC coprocessor. On 60 cores (1 threads per core), MS-BFS-Graft achieves 28Â-36Â speedups for different classes of graphs. By contrast, PR achieves 4Â-7Â and PF achieves 6Â-50Â speedups on the same number of cores. As discussed before, PF might show super linear scaling initially on some networks (e.g., 7Â speedups on 4 cores in Fig. 9b ). We note that the speedup achieved by MS-BFS-Graft on 60 cores of the KNC coprocessor is comparable to the reported 15Â-20Â speedup achieved by traditional BFS on 31 cores of a Knights Ferry (KNF) coprocessor [CITATION_1] . However, the performance of the latter BFS implementation degraded by a factor of two when four hardware threads were used in each core [CITATION_2] . By contrast, our more involved matching algorithm continues to scale when several hardware threads are used in each core and achieves up to 2Â speedups when we go from 60 to 240 threads on KNC.",
